[2026-05-20--16:57:59]Agent: <Findings version="1" source="Design" source_version="1">
    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--1">
        <ItemID>CMP--1</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            The ConnectedComponents of CMP--1 reference only CMP--2 and CMP--10, but CMP--1 textually depends on signals provided by other components (e.g. ExplorationEvents from CMP--11, PoseEstimate from CMP--9, PL_PathPlanningResponse from CMP--4, ReturnToStartStatus / SecondRunExecutionStatus likely from CMP--8, SensorAvailabilityStatus from CMP--7, GoalRegionInfo from CMP--5). These producing/consuming relationships are not modeled as ConnectedComponent entries, so the component interface is incomplete and inconsistent with the described behavior.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            For CMP--1, add explicit ConnectedComponent entries for all interacting components (at least CMP--2, CMP--3, CMP--4, CMP--5, CMP--6/CMP--8 if they provide status, CMP--7, CMP--9, CMP--11, and any event-queue provider), and move all listed Receive/Transmit signals to the appropriate ConnectedComponent blocks, ensuring every signal has a clearly identified provider and consumer consistent with other components’.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--2">
        <ItemID>CMP--2</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            CMP--2’s ConnectedComponents block is structurally and logically inconsistent:
            - It declares &lt;Identifier&gt;CMP--3&lt;/Identifier&gt; as the first connected component, but the Transmit side sends FGM_FrontierSet and FGM_SelectedTarget and Receive side consumes MC_FrontierRequest and TimeAwarePlanningInfo, which by semantics are interactions with CMP--1 (mission control) and CMP--11 (time limit), not CMP--3 (grid map).
            - Grid map queries (GM_MapQuery) are modeled as a Signal under the same CMP--3 ConnectedComponent, but CMP--3’s own design exposes GM_MapData and GM_ClassificationChangeEvent, not GM_MapQuery.
            - The second ConnectedComponent uses Identifier CMP--4 and handles PL_TravelTimeEstimates, which is consistent, but overall producer/consumer mapping is unclear.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Split CMP--2’s interactions into correct ConnectedComponents:
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--1 carrying MC_FrontierRequest (Receive) and FGM_SelectedTarget (Transmit).
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--3 carrying frontier-related map access (rename GM_MapQuery/GM_MapData to a consistent pair).
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--11 for TimeAwarePlanningInfo (Receive).
            - Keep CMP--4 for PL_TravelTimeEstimates.
            Ensure the signal naming matches the opposite side in the other components.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--3">
        <ItemID>CMP--3</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            CMP--3 describes receiving MM_MapUpdateRequest from the mapping module and sending GM_MapData / GM_ClassificationChangeEvent to planning and exploration modules, but:
            - No ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--6 exists on CMP--3, even though it is the provider/consumer of MM_MapUpdateRequest and the local states GM_CellAndWallStates.
            - No ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--2 is defined, although CMP--2 consumes map access for frontier detection.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Add explicit ConnectedComponent elements to CMP--3:
            - One for CMP--6 with Receive MM_MapUpdateRequest and possibly Transmit GM_CellAndWallStates (if kept).
            - One for CMP--2 (frontier generation) and one for CMP--4 (planner) exposing map access as per GM_MapData/GM_MapQuery.
            Ensure all such signals are consistently named and referenced by the counterpart components.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--4">
        <ItemID>CMP--6</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            CMP--6’s ConnectedComponents have mismatched Identifiers relative to the described semantics:
            - The first ConnectedComponent has Identifier CMP--7 but Transmit/Receive signals correspond to interactions with the grid map module (GM_CellAndWallStates, MM_MapUpdateRequest), which should be CMP--3.
            - The second ConnectedComponent has Identifier CMP--8 but includes SAL_FilteredSensorData and PoseEstimate as Receive signals, which originate from CMP--7 (sensor abstraction) and CMP--9 (pose estimation), not CMP--8 (motion control).
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Correct CMP--6’s ConnectedComponents as follows:
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--3: Receive GM_CellAndWallStates (or GM_MapData) and Transmit MM_MapUpdateRequest.
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--7: Receive SAL_FilteredSensorData.
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--9: Receive PoseEstimate and possibly PoseAlignedFlag.
            - A ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--8: exchange MM_WallDetectionResult and MM_CollisionRiskEvent as already described.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--5">
        <ItemID>CMP--7</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            CMP--7’s ConnectedComponents conflate low-level hardware APIs with other components:
            - The ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--10 transmits SAL_SampledSensorData and receives Sched_ControlLoopTick; this is acceptable.
            - The ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--6 correctly models SAL_FilteredSensorData and SensorAvailabilityStatus, but its Receive signals RawUltrasonicApi and RawIrApi are described as direct calls to ultrasonic_get_distance() and infrared_get_*_status(), which are hardware APIs, not separate software components defined in the design.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Either:
            - Remove RawUltrasonicApi and RawIrApi as ConnectedComponent signals and describe the hardware calls purely in the Execution text, or
            - Introduce a dedicated hardware interface component (e.g., CMP--HARDWARE) and reference it via ConnectedComponent Identifier, aligning with other documents.
            Ensure ConnectedComponents only capture inter-software-component communication, not function calls to hardware drivers, unless those are modeled as components.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--6">
        <ItemID>CMP--8</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            CMP--8’s ConnectedComponents do not match their Identifiers:
            - The ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--4 should represent interaction with the Path Planner, but it Transmit MC_PathExecutionStatus and Receive MC_MotionCommand, which in the rest of the design are signals to/from mission control (CMP--1), not planner (CMP--4).
            - Emergency-stop behavior is modeled as transmitting EM_StopCommand to CMP--7, which is conceptually just a call to motor_set; CMP--7 is a sensor layer and not responsible for actuators.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Adjust CMP--8 connections:
            - Define a ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--1: Receive MC_MotionCommand and Transmit execution status (ReturnToStartStatus / SecondRunExecutionStatus or a unified status signal).
            - If CMP--4 interacts directly with CMP--8 (e.g., for path streaming), model that explicitly; otherwise remove CMP--4 from this component’s ConnectedComponents.
            - For motors, keep a ConnectedComponent with Identifier CMP--10 (or a dedicated Motor Interface component) for Motion_MotorCommand only; remove EM_StopCommand as an inter-component signal and keep emergency stop as behavior invoking motor_set internally.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="DESIGN--1--7">
